<FIRST>r a PM-EXP--Voyager'sEyes     07-02 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EXP--Voyager's Eyes,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Telescopes Around The World Watch Voyager Signals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-EXP--Voyager-Neptune</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT MYGATT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLAINS OF SAN AUGUSTIN, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imagine a 20-watt
refrigerator light bulb burning in the dark, 2.75 billion miles away.
   Now imagine the sophisticated eyes needed to see the light.
   Voyager 2, heading for Neptune, is emitting 20 watts of radio
signals, information coded in binary bits _ ones and zeros _ on the
space probe's health and from its scientific instruments and cameras.
   ``Think of that lightbulb as flickering, and that flickering
contains the information that Voyager is sending back to us,'' said
Bill Brundage, Voyager preparation manager for the Very Large Array
radio telescope.
   The signals have become fainter since Voyager's encounters with
Jupiter in 1979, Saturn in 1981 and Uranus in 1986. The signals, and
commands sent to the 12-year-old probe, take four hours and six
minutes to cross 2.75 billion miles at the speed of light. Larger
antennas and more sensitive receivers are needed on Earth to receive
the signals, and more power is needed to transmit commands to the
craft, which will pass fly within 3,000 miles of Neptune on Aug. 24.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration's Deep Space
Network is used to talk to Voyager. The DSN has three complexes:
Goldstone in California's Mojave Desert; Madrid, Spain; and
Tidbinbilla, Australia, near Canberra.
   When Voyager flew by Uranus, the California and Australian
listening posts used three antenna dishes each _ one 210 feet across
and two 112 feet _ and the Madrid station used one of each, said
Mary Beth Murrill, a spokeswoman for the NASA Jet Propulsion
Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif. The Canberra complex also was linked
to Australia's 210-foot Parkes Radio Astronomy Telescope.
   For Neptune, the 210-foot dishes at Goldstone, Canberra and
Madrid have been increased to 230 feet and another 112-foot antenna
was built at Madrid. In addition, the VLA is being used in
conjunction with Goldstone, Parkes again is linked with Canberra,
and a Japanese telescope will be added to the network.
   The different sites ensure that at least one station can
communicate with the spacecraft despite the Earth's rotation,
Brundage said.
   ``The VLA alone gives us almost a third more images than if we
didn't have it,'' said Norm Haynes, Voyager project manager at JPL.
   The VLA is a one-of-a-kind space-age erector set sitting on an
ancient lake bed. The site is skirted by four mountain ranges,
protecting it from much of the electronic interference from
television, radios, aircraft and the like.
   It consists of 27 white dish-shaped antennas, each 82 feet in
diameter, 92 feet high and weighing 235 tons. The dishes sit on the
Plains of San Augustin amid tumbleweed, cattle and sparse vegetation
at an altitude of 7,000 feet.
   The dishes are arranged along three arms of railroad track, laid
out in the shape of a Y. Two arms are 13 miles long and the third is
11.8 miles. The Earth rotates the Y like a turntable, creating
images that have the same detail as if using a radio telescope up to
26 miles in diameter.
   A special 36-wheel transporter moves each antenna to one of 72
observation stations along the three arms. This acts like a zoom
lens _ the farther out the dishes, the higher the resolution; the
closer in, the larger the field of view.
   NASA spent $6.5 million to equip each dish to receive Voyager's
signals. It also set up special techniques and installed two big
diesel generators to guard against lightning-caused power
fluctuations during the thunderstorm season.
   The separation of the listening posts around the world _ just
like the separation of the VLA dishes _ strengthen the sensitivity
of the network. The signal VLA gets from Voyager is sent via
satellite to Goldstone, where the two signals are combined, decoded
and sent via microwave to JPL in Pasadena.
</TEXT>
