<FIRST>u a AM-Abortion-Convention 2ndLd-Writethru a0613 07-02 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Convention, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0613,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen Warn Against Complacency In Anti-Abortion Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Missouri governor blaming
abortion for problems of youth; picks up 6th graf, `In the...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion Opponents, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governor of Missouri told
anti-abortion lobbyists Saturday that legalized abortion contributes
to dropouts, suicides and low self-esteem among youth.
   Gov. John Ashcroft, speaking to the National Right to Life
Committee's annual convention two days before the Supreme Court was
expected to rule on a Missouri case that could determine the future
of legalized abortion in America, said abortions contributed to a
``vacuum of values'' among the youth.
   ``What kind of signal are we as a society sending them about the
value of life? We need to send an unmistakable message that there is
a fundamental value in life itself,'' he said.
   The law being reviewed by the Supreme Court puts restrictions on
abortions and defines life as beginning at conception. Upholding the
Missouri law, or even parts of it, could reverse or seriously erode
the 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision legalizing abortion.
   ``The Roe decision is simply a miserable failure,'' Ashcroft
said, drawing loud applause. ``And I hope that the Supreme Court
announces it is overturning the Roe decision and giving back to the
states the right to make public policy.''
   The court has said it may rule Monday on the case, Webster vs.
Reproductive Health Services, or delay its decision for further
review.
   Earlier Saturday, U.S. Rep. Chris Smith, R-N.J., told delegates
they must not become complacent in light of victories the movement
has achieved over the last 20 years.
   ``We've got to regroup. We've got to rededicate. We've got to
realize that the fight is just beginning,'' Smith said.
   ``Over the past two decades, our message has been getting
through. Our efforts are bearing fruit. Without us, it would have
gotten worse,'' said Smith, one of three congressmen with strong
anti-abortion records in the House.
   In the Minneapolis-St. Paul suburb of Robbinsdale, meanwhile,
about 300 protesters on both sides of the issue picketed and sang
Saturday morning outside a clinic where abortions are performed.
   Dixie Riley of the National Organization for Women said NOW
representatives were on hand ``to make sure that the women can get
into the clinic and exercise their constitutional right _ for as
long as it lasts. We all know the Roe v. Wade decision is being
reconsidered.''
   Reps. James Oberstar, D-Minn., and Henry Hyde, R-Ill., also
addressed the group.
   ``America ... has been called a disposable society, but that
shouldn't include people,'' Oberstar said.
   Many religious groups support the anti-abortion position, he said.
   ``But there is more than religion alone to guide us in this issue
because there's incontrovertible medical and biological evidence
that life begins at conception,'' the congressman said.
   Hyde said abortion is just another indication of decay in the
morals of America. The high incidence of alcoholism and drug abuse
and the lack of religious guidance for many people are other
indications, he said.
   ``The moral infrastructure of America has broken down,'' Hyde
said. ``We must be the rebuilders.''
   ``The greatest civil right, the greatest human right of all, is
the right to life,'' he said.
</TEXT>
