<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--India-Doctors     07-02 0111</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--India-Doctors,0113</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors End 47-Day-Old Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 doctors at state-run
hospitals ended a 47-day-old strike Sunday that had paralyzed
medical care to the city's poor.
   The doctors are to return to work Monday, according to
negotiators for the government and the Junior Doctors Federation.
   The agreement ending the strike was signed following negotiations
that stretched through the night. The doctors had demanded pay
raises, higher allowances for not being allowed to maintain private
practices, and schedules for promotion.
   Under the agreement, the doctors will receive raises of $25 a
month, less than half they had sought. Their monthly salaries
average $200 to $269.
</TEXT>
