<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Rebels Killed in Clash Near U.S. Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops clashed with
communist guerrillas in a village near the U.S.-run Clark Air Base,
and eight rebels and a government soldier were killed, the military
reported Sunday.
   Four soldiers were wounded in the battle Saturday near Angeles
City, 50 miles northwest of Manila, a report from the Philippine
Constabulary headquarters in Manila said.
   Troops recovered six M-16 rifles and rebel documents from the
slain New People's Army guerrillas, the report said.
   The rebels were surrounded at a house in Duquit village, about a
mile from the air base. The house had been under surveillance for
some time, said a constabulary soldier who requested anonymity. The
soldier was contacted by telephone from Angeles City, home of Clark
Air Base.
   He said the rebels fired first and troops retaliated after
ordering civilians out of the house. He quoted officials as saying
the rebels could have been preparing for operations in the city to
coincide with July 4 celebrations. July 4 also is celebrated in the
Philippines as Fil-American Friendship Day.
   The New People's Army has been fighting 20 years to set up a
Marxist system in the Philippines. It also wants the removal of U.S.
military facilities from the Philippines.
   In October 1987, rebels killed three Americans and a Filipino of
U.S. descent during a series of ambushes outside Clark Air Base.
