<HEAD>Thatcher Worried About German-French Axis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher was quoted Sunday
as saying Britain has an influential role to play in Europe because
many countries do not want everything determined by a
``German-French axis.''
   She was responding to questions about the recent European
Economic Community summit in Madrid, during which Britain was the
most vocal opponent of a single European currency and a central bank
for the 12 EEC countries.
   ``Let us face it, many other countries really do not want
everything to be determined by a kind of German-French axis,'' she
was quoted as saying in an interview with The Sunday Express.
   ``A number of the smaller countries realize the enormous part
that Britain has played both in Europe's history and in her
liberation and still pays in having very open financial markets,''
she was quoted as saying.
