<DOCNO> AP890702-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-89 1136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HUD-Dean Bjt   07-02 0932</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Dean, Bjt,910</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deborah Gore Dean: There to Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The letter to Deborah Gore Dean, an aide to the
secretary of Housing and Urban Development, didn't waste any words.
   ``Dear Debbie,'' it began.
   ``HELP!
   ``Paul''
   Paul Goulding, a financial consultant who was working on behalf
of a community organization, said he was at the end of his rope that
July day a few years ago.
   In his case, the plea did not work. In many others, it did.
   An examination of Ms. Dean's correspondence during her years at
the top of HUD shows that help was her business _ particularly for
certain developers and well-connected Republican consultants.
   Relatively few of the hundreds of letters released by HUD were
signed by Ms. Dean. However, accompanying documents show that she
gave the final approval to many letters over the signature of her
boss, then-housing Secretary Samuel R. Pierce Jr. They were then
signed by a machine at her command.
   Ms. Dean, 34, is at the center of investigations of influence
peddling at HUD, where she has been identified as the person who
controlled millions of dollars for housing rehabilitation.
   She has refused to testify before a congressional panel
investigating HUD, citing her constitutional right against self
incrimination.
   And aside from earlier interviews with The Wall Street Journal,
she has avoided contact with the news media. Last week, when she
accidentally answered a call at her lawyer's office from The
Associated Press, she politely but firmly declined to talk and
quickly put her attorney on the phone.
   Her rise through the ranks at the department was stymied only by
the Senate, which derailed her nomination to be assistant HUD
secretary. But it was from her post as executive assistant to
Pierce, the job she held until she left the department in 1987, that
she exerted her control.
   Goulding said in an interview that he had gotten nowhere in
trying to persuade HUD to boost a rent subsidy for a housing
development on the south side of Providence, R.I. HUD already had
given money to fix up the project, but it needed higher rent
subsidies to make it financially workable, he said.
   Goulding wound up seeking the help of Ms. Dean.
   ``I took a shot and called her,'' he said. ``She was always very
polite to me and very nice and offering to be of help but I didn't
get anywhere, never translated into anything positive,
unfortunately.''
   Goulding wasn't alone.
   Members of Congress wrote to Pierce to push for projects back
home. Often they got letters back saying all the money had already
been spent.
   In the spring of 1985, for example, Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., wrote
a ``Dear Sam'' letter to Pierce. Although the news was bad, the tone
was friendly when he got back letter addressed ``Dear John'' and
signed just ``Sam.''
   The letter's tone was set by Ms. Dean, as was the signature. On
formal occasions she would have the machine, called an autopen, sign
``Samuel R. Pierce Jr.,'' but when the mood called for it, she would
have the letter signed ``Sam.''
   Internal file slips from HUD, carrying the initials of everyone
in the chain of command reviewing a particular piece or
correspondence, indicate that the final stop before the mail box was
at Ms. Dean's desk. It is not known whether Pierce himself saw any
of the correspondence because his initials are not on the slips.
   Pierce, whose hands-off style of management at HUD has been
sharply criticized in the wake of disclosures about political
influence, costly misjudgments and outright stealing that plagued
the department, has said he was betrayed by his aides and singled
out Ms. Dean.
   ``She liked power,'' Pierce said in an interview with The New
York Times. ``She liked the idea that, `I can call the shots, I can
get this for you if I want, I can stomp on you, I can kill you' _
that's the kind of thing she liked.''
   Among the people who beat a path to her door were former Interior
Secretary James Watt, GOP political consultant Paul Manafort, GOP
fund-raiser and now ambassador-designate to Luxembourg Fred Bush,
and Philip Winn, a former HUD official who now is ambassador to
Switzerland. All of them came away with money for the projects they
represented, bringing some of them six-figure fees from grateful
clients.
   But Ms. Dean, who held little formal authority at the department,
occasionally invoked that lack of official power to give people the
brush off.
   ``First, I feel I must explain once again,'' she wrote in 1985 to
Allen Moore, who was seeking funds for a Los Angeles project.
``Neither I nor Secretary Pierce have any authority to designate
moderate rehabilitation funds to you or your client. I have tried to
make this clear in the past.
   ``They are issued on a competitive basis, and there are far more
requests than there are units available,'' Ms. Dean wrote.
   No one would dispute that there were more requests for help than
there was help available, but few people would agree that the HUD
funds were awarded in fair competition.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., chairman of a subcommittee
investigating HUD, has called the notion of competition ``a sham and
an illusion.''
   Goulding, who said he was personally hurt for a while that his
social contacts with Ms. Dean did not translate into money, has
become forgiving over time.
   ``Unfortunately, Debbie sometimes tells you things that aren't
necessarily accurate,'' Goulding said. ``It's not because she means
badly, it's that she over commits herself.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
