<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Suicides     07-02 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Suicides,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>35 Soldiers A Year Commit Suicide In The Israeli Army</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 35 soldiers in the Israeli army commit
suicide each year, the head of the army's personnel department said
in a newspaper interview published Sunday.
   Thirty-two soldiers committed suicide from April 1988 to April
1989, Maj. Gen. Matan Vilnai told the daily Haaretz. The military
command confirmed the figures.
   Vilnai's interview was a departure from the military's customary
reluctance to provide such data, which could have a negative effect
on soldiers' morale.
   No figures on attempted suicides were given. The newspaper and
army said the average of 35 suicides was for recent years, but they
did not say which years.
   Neither Vilnai nor the military command knew if any of the
suicides were related to the 18-month-old Palestinian uprising
against Israeli rule in the occupied Gaza Strip and West Bank.
   Vilnai said 30 percent of those who killed themselves were
reservists troubled by family and financial problems. They are
pushed into the act by the availability of weapons and the hope that
relatives will get financial compensation from the army, he said.
   Israeli men are drafted at the age of 18 for a three-year period
of regular duty, and serve up to 40 days a year as reservists until
age 55. Women are drafted for two years of regular service, and some
of them are required to serve as reservists afterward.
   The Tel Aviv-based Jaffee Center for Strategic Studies says
Israel has a 170,000-strong standing army and 370,000 reserves.
   Vilnai said an average of two to three female soldiers commit
suicide every year. He said most of the regular soldiers who have
killed themselves did so during the first year of their military
duty.
   Haaretz said the army's personnel department recently issued
instructions on how to spot troubled soldiers to prevent suicides.
   However, the paper said ``This activity is quite limited since it
is feared that dealing with the question of suicide may in fact
increase the number of suicides.''
</TEXT>
