<SECOND>AM-Baker-Asia,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Heading To Tokyo For Meeting With Aid Donor Nations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III sets out
Monday for Japan where he will meet with representatives of other
aid donor nations to discuss expanding economic assistance to the
Philippines.
   The so-called Multilateral Assistance Initiative envisions $1
billion a year from aid donors over the next five years as well as
foreign investments totaling a similar amount.
   Aside from the United States, representatives from the European
Economic Community, Canada and Australia, among others, are expected
to attend.
   The meeting is being hosted by the World Bank.
   After a one-day visit to Tokyo, Baker heads for Brunei where he
will meet with foreign ministers of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations
   The major topics are expected to be the evolving situation in
China and the status of international efforts to promote a peaceful
settlement to the Cambodian conflict.
   The ASEAN members are Thailand, the Philippines, Malaysia,
Singapore, Indonesia and Brunei.
   Afterward, Baker heads for Poland where he will join President
Bush next Sunday at the start of his four-nation European visit.
   En route, Baker will spend a day and a half in Oman. The visit
there is described as both a rest stop and also an opportunity to
meet with officials of the government of Oman, with which the United
States has had close ties for years.
