<FIRST>r a AM-JazzFestival     07-02 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jazz Festival,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Latin Jazz Stars Jam At JVC Jazz Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Latin jazz night has become a fixture at the
annual JVC Jazz Festival, and Saturday night's edition provided a
fine cross-section of jazz, salsa and entertaining combinations of
the two.
   The headliners were the Fania Six, all-star musicians from Puerto
Rico. They were preceded by flutist Herbie Mann, whose 35-year
career has been on the rise during the last few years since he
formed the Brazilian group Brasil Jazz.
   The evening was opened _ and nearly stolen _ by the fiery
Dominican jazz pianist Michel Camilo. The crowded bill limited
Camilo's set to about half an hour, but in that time he generated
enough energy to light a town of 10,000 for a week.
   Camilo's command of the piano is unlike anything else heard in
jazz. He is a consummate technician. Yet he keeps his technique
under the tightest control, never allowing it to outrun his musical
ideas.
   He played only his own compositions, taken from his latest album.
The tunes revealed him to be a composer of considerable depth and
inventiveness, particularly in the beautiful ballad ``Nostalgia.''
   He introduced as his special guest Paquito D'Rivera, in whose
group Camilo first came to prominence. The two have recorded
together but no longer tour together. But they haven't lost their
rapport; D'Rivera was ready to match Camilo's fireworks.
   Herbie Mann's group was a disappointment, but that may not have
been entirely his fault. The restraint and sophistication of Mann's
Brazilian-inflected group was a poor choice to follow Camilo.
Although Mann is the bigger name, he should have opened for Camilo.
   His second problem was a poorly adjusted sound system. The bass,
critical for the rhythmic sway of Brazilian music, was inaudible
through much of Mann's set.
   He repeatedly indicated to off-stage technicians that he couldn't
hear himself play, but the problem apparently was never corrected.
   His special guest was Dave Valentin, a flutist who Mann recalled
encouraging when Valentin was 16. Despite the sound problems,
Valentin's arrival on stage gave Mann's group some needed energy,
and it became clear that the group had not been at its best.
   The highlight of the evening was the last set by the Fania Six, a
group of Puerto Rican musicians (some of them based in New York)
associated with the Fania record label. They are Johnny Pacheco on
flute and vocals, Ray Barretto on congas, Papo Lucca on piano, Bobby
Valentin on bass, Robert Roena on bongos and Nicky Marrero on
timbales.
   This was classic salsa. They rhythms were irresistible, the
melodies engaging and the solos impressive. Pacheco made part of the
set into a flute extravaganza when he invited Valentin and Mann on
stage.
   The three flutists played off one another, reaching peaks they
couldn't have scaled alone. It was one of those special moments that
can occur in jazz festivals, in which artists who don't normally
perform together are suddenly thrust on stage at the same time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
