<FIRST>r i AM-FuriousFliers 1stLd-Writethru   07-02 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Furious Fliers, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0659,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irate Airline Passengers Scrap Flight to Protest Delays</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with background on previous similar incident involving
Orion, efforts to reach airline for comment; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers walked out of the
Manchester Airport early Sunday and refused to travel to Florida on
a jumbo jet delayed for two days by three separate mechanical
problems, the airport manager said.
   Roy Edwards said 167 passengers got refunds. ``They were clearly
sick to death of the whole thing,'' he said.
   It was the second such incident in four days involving North
Carolina-based Orion Air.
   The ordeal began when the Boeing 747, owned by Orion and
chartered to the British firm Air Tours, was delayed in Florida
because of an ``oil problem.''
   It finally left Orlando, Fla., but then developed an electrical
problem on its way to Manchester on Friday. When it arrived in
Manchester, a fault was found with the flap control shafts, Edwards
said.
   A spare part was flown from London's Gatwick Airport, but it was
the wrong part, Edwards said.
   The plane finally left Manchester for Florida on Sunday, 47 hours
late and with only 329 of the 496 passengers who had booked seats.
   Orion is based in Raleigh, N.C. No one answered the telephone at
the company headquarters Sunday, and the recording on the answering
machine advised callers to try again during business hours Monday
through Friday.
   In Edmonton, Alberta, 53 British tourists refused to board
another Orion Airlines Boeing 747 that was forced to land in the
Canadian city Thursday night for repairs. They demanded that the
airline make other arrangements to fly them home.
   The aircraft had been repaired four times during a trip that was
supposed to take about 480 passengers on a charter flight from
Manchester to Hawaii and back again.
   To make matters worse, a bus taking passengers from the Edmonton
Inn to the airport caught fire Friday night. No one was hurt but the
passengers had to wait for another bus to go the rest of the way.
   The plane was on the way from Hawaii back to England when it had
to land in Edmonton. Many of the passengers lost their patience. It
finally left Edmonton International Airport at about 1:30 a.m.
Saturday without the 53 people who had refused to board.
</TEXT>
