<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-89 1404EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Khrushchev     07-02 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Khrushchev,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Newspaper Says Khrushchev Denounced Colleagues in Purges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev was quick
to denounce his colleagues as disloyal during the Stalinist purges
of the 1930s, a Soviet newspaper reported Sunday.
   ``We need to destroy those scoundrels,'' Sovietskaya Rossia
quoted Khrushchev as saying at the 1937 conference of the Moscow
Communist Party organization. ``While destroying one, two or 10, we
are doing the deed on behalf of millions.
   ``We should step over the dead bodies of our enemies for the sake
of the people.''
   The article was based on previously closed archives and written
by historian A. Ponomarev, assistant director of the history
institute of the Moscow Communist Party.
   Khrushchev, who rose to lead the Soviet Union from 1953 to 1964,
published his memoirs in the West but glossed over his role in the
purges of his predecessor, Josef Stalin, who killed millions of
Soviets in consolidating his control. Excerpts from Khrushchev's
autobiography were published in the Soviet Union this year.
   The newspaper report indicated that Khrushchev rose by joining in
Stalin's accusations of disloyalty.
   ``He was part of a new group whose members were more loyal to
Stalin _ who entered the leadership due to their active fight
against rightists,'' wrote Ponomarev.
   When Khrushchev moved up to Ukrainian party leader, he had words
of praise for his successor, A.I. Igarov, the article said. But
within months, Igarov was being blamed for mistakes, and Khrushchev
joined the chorus, according to the report.
   ``This time Khrushchev spoke of him as an old enemy, hired by
Trotskyites and rightists who had been involved in hostile actions
in Leningrad and Moscow,'' Ponomarev wrote.
   Lev Trotsky was a Bolshevik rival who was denounced by Stalin,
forced into exile and eventually assassinated in Mexico. Thousands
of Soviets were put to death on charges of conspiring with Trotsky
against the Soviet leadership.
   In the early years of Stalin's attacks on his colleagues,
Khrushchev was party chief of a workers' school called
Promakademiya. The article said that as soon as Khrushchev took the
post in 1930, 40 Communists were hauled before the party leadership
to answer questions on their loyalty.
   The newspaper also said Khrushchev was one of the first to accuse
Nikolas Bukharin, a member of the ruling Politburo in the 1920s who
was ousted by Stalin in 1929. In fact, Khrushchev had to retract his
early criticism after the party newspaper Pravda published a letter
praising Bukharin, the article said.
   Later, the tide turned against Bukharin and he was executed in
1938.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890702-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-89 1440EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ChurchofChrist 1stLd-Writethru a0686 07-02 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church of Christ, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0686,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denomination's Choice Of Home: New York or Cleveland?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last 3 grafs, bgng `The nominee...', with 3 grafs to CORRECT
name of group to United Church of Christ, add sentence explaining that
Church of Christ, United Church of Christ are distinct.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Church of Christ, a
progressive denomination with roots in the earliest American
colonies, is struggling to end a 10-year battle over whether its
national offices should leave New York City.
   The 703 delegates of the denomination's 17th General Synod hoped
to decide Monday whether to combine its national offices _ now
scattered in three New York City locations _ in a single New York
location or move them to Cleveland.
   Synod delegates will also elect a new president on Monday. One of
the candidates is a woman who if elected would become the first
woman president of a major Protestant group in the United States.
   Leaders of the 32-year-old, 1.8 million-member denomination
expected the synod to handily approve a study committee's
recommendation to move the headquarters denomination to Cleveland.
Presbyterian and Lutheran denominations involved in mergers also
have moved from the city in recent years.
   But, after four days of meetings, the synod has become sharply
divided over whether the cost savings available in Cleveland are
worth losing some ecumenical ties in New York.
   Those favoring New York wear apple stickers on their name tags.
Delegates favoring Cleveland wear a sailboat.
   ``Most people feel that there are some compelling arguments on
either side,'' said the Rev. Reiss Potterveld, senior minister at
Congregational Church of Northridge, Calif., near Los Angeles.
   Potterveld chairs the 33-member committee that for nearly seven
hours on Saturday reviewed the earlier committee's study of the
issue. His committee set up Monday's decision by endorsing the
Cleveland proposal 21-10 with two abstentions.
   The UCC's last national meeting, in 1987, rejected a
recommendation to move the headquarters to St. Louis, ordering the
formation of a study committee instead.
   ``People are sick of this,'' the UCC's Evan Golder said, adding
that another deferral is unlikely. The headquarters debate has raged
for 10 years, he said, since the denomination was forced by a
landlord's decision and the New York rental market to split its
offices.
   No poll of the full delegation had been taken on the issue. But a
proposal already on the synod floor would scrap the committees'
recommendation and move two of the New York UCC offices to the third
office at the Interchurch Center, which houses 65 church and other
non-profit organizations.
   The Ohio delegation, more than 70 people, is the synod's largest,
and its leaders have lobbied hard for a move to Cleveland,
particularly among large delegations from nearby states.
   Critics say a move from New York would diminish the UCC's
standing in the ecumenical community.
   ``This church has a historic and strong involvement in the
ecumenical movement,'' Potterveld said. ``This move will put certain
hardships on that. Both committees recognize that. It (ecumenism) is
part of our heritage and will continue to be part of our future.''
   But not all agree the UCC's ecumenical efforts are best served in
New York, and supporters of the move to Cleveland say it would save
millions in rent and other costs and bridge a symbolic gap between
the national and local church.
   The nominees for president of the denomination are the Rev. Paul
H. Sherry of Chicago and the Rev. Yvonne Delk of Union City, N.J. If
Delk wins, she would be the first woman president of the United
Church of Christ or other major Protestant denomination.
   The president of the UCC is the denomination's senior minister,
chief executive and its official representative in ecumenical
relations. While the president has no doctrinal or authoritarian
power over the denomination's members, the position is widely viewed
as an important theological platform.
   The denomination formed in the 1957 merger of the Congregational
Christian Churches and the Evangelical and Reformed Church. It is
unrelated to the Church of Christ, a loosely associated group of
conservative churches.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
