<DOCNO> AP890702-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-89 1452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-TiredDoctors Bjt   07-02 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tired Doctors, Bjt,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Rules Aimed at Protecting New York Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York over the weekend became the first state
to limit the grueling work hours of interns and residents to reduce
the risk of error by dazed and exhausted doctors-in-training.
   New York, which trains 16 percent of the nation's doctors, is
leading a national movement away from the century-old tradition of
36-hour shifts and 100-hour work weeks for postgraduate trainees in
medicine. The Health Department now limits shifts to 24 hours and
the work week to 80 hours.
   Several hospitals in the city had already implemented the 24-hour
rules, and a medical council is preparing guidelines that will be
enforceable nationwide.
   Long hours have been ``a rite of passage for years and years,''
said Dr. Joseph Sachter, chief emergency room resident at
Metropolitan Hospital in New York City. ``But there's been an
astonishing change in two years.''
   Proponents of the tradition say shunning sleep toughens young
doctors to the rigors of medicine and lets them study the
progression of a patient's illness. Critics say bleary-eyed
residents endanger patients _ and can even kill them.
   ``You come in pretty blind in July and August _ it's no secret
the mortality rates are the highest when the interns are brand new.
You don't know what's going on even with an enormous amount of
direction,'' said a 33-year-old New York City intern who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   State Health Commissioner Dr. David Axelrod said today's doctors
must learn more than their predecessors, make more decisions and
treat sicker patients.
   ``Is it ideal if a resident works 24 hours? No _ but it's a lot
better than 36 hours at a time,'' said Sachter.
   The Hospital Association of New York State and Blue Cross, backed
by the state medical society, have sued to block the regulations,
charging they will be too costly. The hospital industry estimates
4,500 to 5,000 workers must be hired statewide to implement the plan.
   A Health Department study of hospitals with high mortality rates
raised serious questions about the quality of supervision and the
dangers posed by resident fatigue. Axelrod appointed a panel to
address the issue after the 1984 death of the daughter of
author-lawyer Sidney Zion.
   Libby Zion, 18, died after going to New York Hospital for
treatment of an earache and fever. A grand jury, while indicting no
one, found Ms. Zion's death resulted from inadequate care and errors
by unsupervised interns and residents.
   ``We have a sense that there are problems related to fatigue. But
it's harder to attribute a poor decision to fatigue and much easier
to determine that supervision was not present,'' said Health
Department spokeswoman Faith Schottenfeld.
   In February, Drs. Dennis H. Novack and David B. Reuben of Rhode
Island Hospital described fatigue-induced mistakes in a letter to
the Journal of the American Medical Association.
   They told of a get-together where residents admitted ``giving the
wrong antibiotic, overlooking diagnoses, mistranscribing orders and
falling asleep while writing up a history.''
   But traditions die hard.
   When Axelrod and Dr. Bertrand Bell, professor at Albert Einstein
College of Medicine, started pressing for reform in 1987, they were
``lambasted and torn apart by the New York medical establishment,''
said Sachter.
   ``Older physicians say: `I did it _ they're going to do it. ... I
think we're coddling these kids,''' Axelrod said in a May speech.
``Our elders don't recognize that medicine has changed.''
   The Chicago-based Accreditation Council for Graduate Medical
Education, the accreditation body for all teaching hospitals in the
United States, is about to issue work limits for some specialties
and strengthen supervision for all of them.
   The guidelines will be phased in as each hospital comes up for
accreditation over the next three or four years, said James
Weinlader, director of residence review committee activities.
   Critics say hospitals rely on residents for cheap labor. They
earn about $30,000 a year, which comes to $6.25 an hour for a
100-hour week. Costs are a big concern to the New York hospital
association, which says two-thirds of the 220 non-profit or public
hospitals it represents lost money in 1988.
   The Health Department has granted hospitals $226 million in
reimbursements for more staff to take over some jobs previously done
by interns and residents. The hospital association says its members
need $149 million more.
   As for enforcement of the regulations, the Health Department will
be satisfied for now with a good-faith effort, said Schottenfeld.
</TEXT>
