<FIRST>r w AM-TeacherFarewell     07-02 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teacher Farewell,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>NEA President Gives Emotional Speech At Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Hatwood Futrell urged America's teachers
to ``embrace change'' and remember her as having ``chalk dust on the
sleeves of her soul'' in an emotional farewell speech Sunday to the
National Education Association.
   Futrell, president of the 2-million-member union for the past six
years, steps down at the end of the summer. A vote on her successor
was scheduled Monday at the annual NEA Representative Assembly
attended by some 8,400 delegates.
   Futrell is widely credited with bringing the NEA into the thick
of education reform and helping it shed an obstructionist image
fueled by attacks by President Reagan and other conservatives in the
past decade.
   In a 17-page speech interrupted more than 60 times by applause,
cheers and standing ovations, Futrell exhorted her members not only
to participate in but to lead the education reform movement.
   ``We need massive, systemwide restructuring, and the plan we
follow must be a plan conceived, written and implemented by the
educators of America,'' she said. ``We have the programs. We have
the organizational expertise to use our collective bargaining power
to impact areas that go far beyond the issue of salary, as critical
as that issue is and always will be.''
   Futrell said NEA must continue to say no to ``the voucher
salesmen, to the tuition tax credit peddlers, to the elitists, the
politically ambitious and the educationally inexperienced _ all
those who think they know our business better than we do.''
   But she also urged the organization, once labeled ``the status
quo incarnate'' by former Education Secretary William Bennett, not
to stand in the path of worthwhile reforms.
   ``We must embrace change and reject reaction,'' she said. ``We
must continue to expand politically and professionally as we have
over the last 20 years, especially the last five years. ... We must
push hard, we must take risks, we must never let up.''
   Futrell, an Alexandria, Va., resident who has not ruled out an
eventual run for Congress, took some parting shots at Reagan and
also at President Bush.
   Bush declined both a pre-election candidate interview with the
group and an invitation to speak this weekend at its meeting. About
one-third of the union consists of registered Republicans, according
to Futrell.
   ``We've had enough of leaders who whittle away at our schools
then complain that the foundation of education is crumbling,''
Futrell said. ``We've had enough of leaders who think education
policy is having their picture taken in a first grade class, just in
time for the nightly news.''
   The departing union chief reiterated NEA calls for full funding
of national education, health and nutrition programs for
disadvantaged children and dismissed conservative criticism of the
group as having a ``cash register mentality.''
   ``The bankers don't apologize for saying they need more
(money),'' she said, referring to the savings and loan crisis. ``The
generals don't apologize. And we're not going to apologize either.''
   Futrell touched on gun control, homelessness, the global economy,
negative campaigning and other broad issues in the course of her
speech, but ended on a personal note that brought her a lengthy
standing ovation.
   ``I am still Mary the teacher who 20 years ago sat where you are
sitting, and I am still a teacher and I always shall be,'' she said.
``So my dear friends, if you remember me, I want you to remember me
as Mary Hatwood Futrell, someone who has chalk dust on the sleeves
of her soul.''
   The two men vying to succeed Futrell are Vice President Keith
Geiger of Michigan and executive committee member John Wilson of
North Carolina. Geiger is generally considered more moderate and
more likely to continue on the course set by Futrell.
</TEXT>
