<SECOND>AM-People,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor William Hurt, currently in a bitter court
fight with ex-lover Sandra Jennings, has kept her ``twisting in the
wind'' for money and treats her ``almost like she's the baby
sitter,'' his brother says.
   Jim Hurt, speaking in the July 10 issue of People magazine, said
Hurt and Jennings were ``foolish in the way they went about having a
child.'' The couple has a 6-year-old son, Alex.
   ``And that led to disaster. I see it as a tragedy,'' said the
actor's younger brother.
   ``In the long run, yes, he took care of them financially,'' Jim
Hurt said. ``But he always kept Sandra guessing as to when the
payment would come in. This attitude of keeping her twisting in the
wind ... is what did most of the damage. Sandra was never a
gold-digger.''
   Jennings is suing Hurt in Manhattan, charging she was his
common-law wife and entitled to half his earnings since 1982. The
couple, who split in 1983, were never married but lived together for
several years, including a few weeks in South Carolina, which
recognizes common-law marriages.
   The enmity between the pair may be the result of old wounds from
those days, Jim Hurt said.
   ``If Sandra's relationship with Bill had been healthier, if he'd
shown her more courtesy over the years, then there wouldn't be such
bitterness now. He treats her almost like she's the baby sitter,''
he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dick Cavett, back in Nebraska for his 35th
high school reunion, said he once had doubts about his career and
thought he was crazy to leave the Cornhusker State.
   Cavett, the entertainer and talk show host who was raised in
Gibbon, Grand Island and Lincoln, said Friday that he loves to
return to Nebraska whenever he gets a chance. And he said he
sometimes wonders how his life would have turned out if he stayed in
his home state.
   He recalled returning to the state once during a period of
``extreme self-doubts and anguish about what I had done with my
life.''
   At the time, he said, he said to himself: ``Why did I ever leave
here? I was insane. This is what people work for, to get to live in
a place like Lincoln.''
   However, Cavett still spends most of his time in Manhattan.
   ``As wretched as New York has gotten in so many ways,'' Cavett
said, ``I still get a thrill every time I cross one of the bridges
and see the skyline. I think, `God, I love being in the midst of all
this.'
   ``But then on the other hand, being in the midst of it, I don't
take advantage of it,'' he said. ``I come out to Lincoln and people
show me their playbills from Broadway shows and say, `Did you think
this was better than that?' and I say, `I didn't see either one of
them.'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SIERRA VISTA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ronald Reagan and
wife Nancy landed here on their way to an unannounced, unofficial
buffalo hunt at a Mexican ranch and game preserve, a newspaper
reported.
   The Sierra Vista Herald said a Reagan spokesman in Los Angeles
would only say that the former first couple was on a private trip.
   The Redo ranch in Mexico was visited twice by Reagan while he was
president, according to Mexican journalist Alma Lorenia, a reporter
in Hermosillo, a Mexican town about 15 miles south of the Arizona
border. Both times, she said, Reagan was officially said to be in
Santa Barbara, Calif.
   Reagan was met at the Sierra Vista Airport on Saturday by U.S.
Secret Service agents, who closed the airport terminal, and was last
observed climbing into a four-wheel-drive vehicle in nearby Bisbee.
   A motorcade of Secret Service vehicles and the Reagan party was
escorted by Cochise County Sheriff Jimmy Judd and several deputies.
   ``I just don't want some crackpot taking a shot at him while he's
in Cochise County,'' Judd said.
   Reagan frequently has visited a Cochise County ranch owned by a
relative of actor Jimmy Stewart, the newspaper reported.
</TEXT>
