<FIRST>r w AM-Dole-Nominee     07-02 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dole-Nominee,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frederick Bush Ambassadorial Nomination In `Deep Trouble'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's nomination of his chief
political fundraiser to be U.S. ambassador to Luxembourg is in
``deep trouble'' because of his involvement in the Housing and Urban
Development scandal, Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole said Sunday.
   ``I would guess it may be a while before he goes to Luxembourg,''
Dole said of Frederick M. Bush, who is no relation to the president
but was the finance director for both his 1980 and 1988 presidential
campaigns.
   ``And if he goes, it may just be as a visitor,'' Dole quipped.
   Frederick Bush was questioned extensively last Thursday and in
May by the House Government Operations Committee about hundreds of
thousands of dollars in consultant fees which his lobbying firm,
Bush &amp; Co., reaped in 1986 and 1987 for HUD projects in Puerto Rico.
   In the testimony, Frederick Bush acknowledged he had contacted
political appointees at HUD but said he did not feel that he had
``political influence'' with them because of his campaign efforts on
behalf of George Bush or his job as deputy director of the vice
president's staff from 1982 to 1984.
   ``I made the distinction between what I call political access and
political influence,'' the 40-year-old ambassador-designate told the
House panel.
   Dole, interviewed on CBS' ``Face the Nation'' program, said he
was not urging the president to withdraw Frederick Bush's nomination.
   ``I'll support the president,'' Dole said, adding, ``but I think
you've got to be realistic in this business. I don't believe ... the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee (is) going to be in any hurry to
confirm his nomination or to report his nomination favorably.''
</TEXT>
