<HEAD>Man Hospitalized After Python Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was in fair condition Sunday after
his pet python wrapped its 15-foot body around him and started
squeezing, cutting off the man's oxygen and blood flow.
   Tom Ortiz of Kansas City lost consciousness Saturday after Tina,
his 50-pound-plus snake, started to constrict him, officials said.
   ``Our treatment at the scene was for a severe constricting
injury,'' said Jerry Overton of Metropolitan Ambulance Services
Trust. ``When we arrived, the patient was in critical condition.''
   Ortiz, 24, was in fair condition Sunday afternoon at St. Luke's
Hospital, where a spokesman said Ortiz had not suffered internal
injuries but was under observation.
   Tina was taken into custody by Kansas City Animal Control
officials, who said they were uncertain what would become of the
snake.
   They didn't know whether Tina meant to harm Ortiz or just give
him a hug. Pythons are non-poisonous and crush their prey to eat.
