<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     07-02 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAU CLAIRE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rick ``Pellet Gun'' Krause lived up to
his nickname, powering a cherry pit nearly 20 yards to defend his
title in an annual contest here.
   Krause, a teacher from Sparta, puckered up and propelled his pit
59 feet, 6 inches Saturday to win the 16th Annual Cherry Pit
Spitting Championship held at the Tree-Mendus Fruit Farm in
southwestern Michigan.
   The effort fell far short of Krause's record 72-foot, 7-inch spit
in last year's competition. Krause blamed a stiff breeze that forced
him to spit into the wind.
   ``If the wind had been the other way, I think it would have been
a record,'' Krause said, adding that he managed six 80-foot spits
while practicing before Saturday's event. ``The pit kind of dies on
you.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WHITE CASTLE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's the Old South in wood and white
paint, and it's available for $9 million.
   Nottoway plantation's 64 rooms, 200 windows and 22 white cypress
columns are for sale. ``A rare opportunity to purchase a part of
American History,'' an advertisement says.
   The three-story landmark near the Mississippi was completed in
1859. Owner Paul Ramsay, an Australian health care mogul, has asked
a Dallas realty company to offer the home for sale. He and a partner
bought it in 1985 for $4.5 million.
   John Lewis of Hoffman Realty said an advertisement for Nottoway
first appeared in The New York Times a week ago. By the end of the
week, he said, six people, all from the New York area, have inquired
about buying Nottoway.
   Lewis described the inquiries as ``very serious'' and said all
six indicated they would continue the plantation's tours, restaurant
and bed and breakfast operations.
   Nottoway first opened its doors to the public in 1980. After
several unprofitable years, Lewis said, the property now is making
money.
   Nottoway was built by John Hampden Randolph, a wealthy sugar cane
planter from a prominent Virginia family. It's famous for its white
ballroom, its white marble mantles, original crystal chandelier and
intricate plaster friezework and medallions.
   It was shelled by a Yankee gunboat during the Civil War, and tour
guides say some bullet holes still can be found in the building's
cypress facade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nanci Stark was born on Grizella Street and has
lived there for all of her 31 years, so when she decided to marry
Phil Gavasto there was only one place to hold the wedding: on
Grizella Street.
   As about 125 friends and neighbors looked on Friday night, the
father of the bride, John A. Stark, escorted Ms. Stark down a
neighbor's driveway into the cul-de-sac, where she stood next to the
groom.
   The lawn was decorated with nine pink flamingos, one dressed as a
bride and another as a groom. The cul-de-sac was decorated with
balloons and a piano stood off to the side of the street.
   Gavasto said he enjoyed the street wedding.
   ``The people here are like an extended family,'' he said. ``The
whole block are exceptional people.''
   The bride and groom plan to live _ where else ? _ on Grizella
Street.
