<FIRST>r i AM-Greece     07-02 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative-Leftist Coalition Government Sworn In</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative Tzannis Tzannetakis was sworn
in Sunday as premier of a conservative-leftist coalition government
formed to end corrupt politics as crowds chanted ``Put the crooks in
jail!''
   The conservative New Democracy Party and the Coalition of the
Left and Progress agreed to the government Saturday on condition it
last only three months and limit its work to ``restoring democratic
institutions and cleansing Greek political life.''
   About 3,000 people gathered outside the Presidential Palace
downtown to applaud the 22 members of the new government as they
entered and departed after being sworn in by Orthodox Archbishop
Serapheim of Athens.
   ``Catharsis, catharsis, put the crooks in jail!'' the crowd
chanted when Tzannetakis appeared.
   Tzannetakis later presided over the government's first Cabinet
meeting. He said financial scandals involving the outgoing socialist
government would be investigated and that justice would be carried
out ``in full and in depth.''
   Parliament convenes Monday, and under the constitution
Tzannetakis has 15 days to present his government's program for
approval.
   Greece's political parties were forced into negotiations to form
a coalition government after none won a majority in the 300-seat
unicameral parliament in elections June 18.
   New Democracy won 145 seats, six short of an absolute majority;
the Coalition of the Left and Progess won 28 seats and outgoing
Premier Andreas Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement, or
PASOK, won 125. A small conservative party and an independent took
the other two seats.
   It was the first time communists have played a role in
determining the formation of Greece's government.
   Investigating a multimillion-dollar scandal allegedly involving
ministers in Papandreou's government will be the focus of the new
government's work.
   That scandal, and the 70-year-old Papandreou's open affair with a
woman half his age while he was married, contributed to his
downfall. He has been hospitalized with a heart and kidney condition.
</TEXT>
