<FIRST>r a AM-DalaiLama     07-02 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dalai Lama,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tibetan Religious Leader to Visit California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dalai Lama, Tibet's exiled spiritual and
political leader, arrives Monday to conduct a three-day teaching
ceremony as part of a Western tour promoting peace and human rights.
   The Tibetan Buddhist leader, who fled Chinese soldiers in his
homeland three decades ago, is using the international outcry over
the bloody crackdown on student demonstrators in Beijing to refocus
attention on repressive Chinese rule in Tibet.
   Tibetan exiles say 800 people have been killed in their homeland
since the Chinese imposed martial law and moved against independence
demonstrators March 5. Official reports of deaths have been much
smaller.
   The protests began a few days before the 30th anniversary of a
failed uprising in Tibet. The Dalai Lama, spiritual and temporal
ruler of the Tibetans since he was 15, fled to India on March 31,
1959, three weeks after the uprising began when Chinese troops
launched a bloody attack.
   He set up his headquarters and a government-in-exile in the
northern Indian city of Dharmsala.
   The 55-year-old Dalai Lama was scheduled to arrive Monday night
after holding interfaith services in Costa Rica and Mexico and
taking part in a peace conference with Costa Rican President Oscar
Arias Sanchez, the Nobel laureate and architect of a peace plan for
Central America. He leaves July 20 for New York to accept a human
rights award.
   He will conduct an intricate ceremony known as the Kalachakra
initiation, or Wheel of Time, for at least 3,000 Buddhists in Santa
Monica. Also scheduled for his visit to Southern California _ home
to 200,000 of the United States' estimated 2.5 million Buddhists _
is a speech on peace open to the general public.
   The lama, known for his wide knowledge of the world's religions
and politics, will meet the news media Friday, give a public speech
Sunday at the Shrine Auditorium downtown and hold teaching sessions
July 10 through July 13 at the Santa Monica Civic Auditorium.
   The auditorium also will be the site of the sacred Wheel of Time
ceremony, conducted only a few times in the West. A lama dance will
be performed July 15. The ceremony itself will run for several hours
a day July 16 through July 18, and a ``long life'' initiation will
take place July 19. The Dalai Lama will be aided by 18 monks.
   Some 3,000 of the auditorium's 4,000 seats had been reserved by
Friday, at a registration fee of $150, said trip spokeswoman Betty
Rogers.
   The ceremony, intended to help believers along the path to
enlightenment, centers on creation of a mandala, a painting crafted
from colored sand, representing Kalachakra, a four-faced god with 24
arms who subdues violence. Laid out in concentric circles, the
painting includes Sanskrit characters, flowers, animals and 722
symbols for Buddhist deities in a many-chambered palace.
   A separate group of monks will create a duplicate mandala at the
Los Angeles County Museum of Natural History from July 6 through
Aug. 17.
   China says it has ruled Tibet for more than seven centuries. Many
Tibetans say they actually were independent for much of that time,
ruled by a Buddhist theocracy headed by the Dalai Lama.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
