<HEAD>Suspected IRA Car Bomb Kills One, Injures Three; Second Bomb Defused</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with IRA suspected, second bomb
defused, officials saying soldier's wife and three children injured. Pickup
9th graf `On June...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspected IRA car bomb exploded on
a British military base Sunday evening, killing a soldier and
injuring his wife and three children, officials said.
   The bomb went off as the man opened the door of the car and his
family waited to get in, police said.
   The attack, in a housing area on the base, was the second in two
weeks on a British installation in West Germany.
   Officials said bomb disposal experts found another explosive
device in the area and defused it. Residents in nearby apartment
buildings were evacuated and police searched for other bombs.
   There was no claim of responsibility for the attack, but
officials suspected the Irish Republican Army, which is fighting to
end British rule in Northern Ireland.
   ``The indications are that this is the kind of attack that can be
attributed to the IRA,'' said Hans-Juergen Foerster, a spokesman for
the federal prosecutor's office in Karlsruhe.
   Squadron Leader Marion Yates, a spokeswoman for the British
military in West Germany, said the explosion ``occurred in a married
living quarters area.
   ``We also understand that three children and a woman were taken
to hospital with injuries,'' she said.
   Hanover police said the injured were the man's wife and three
children and that they were were slightly injured in the blast.
   The names of the victims were not immediately released. Police
and British officials believed the soldier owned the car.
   On June 19, a bomb ripped through the living quarters at a
British military barracks near Osnabrueck. No one was injured in the
blast, but police suspect the IRA was responsible for the attack.
   On June 14, West German prosecutors indicted two suspected IRA
members on attempted murder charges in 1987 and 1988 bombing attacks
aimed at the British military that wounded 46 people, most of them
West Germans.
   The IRA has attacked British troops in Europe in its campaign to
force the British out of Northern Ireland and unite the
predominantly Protestant province with the mostly Roman Catholic
Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
