<FIRST>r a AM-ChurchClosings     07-02 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church Closings,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Holds Service Despite Order To Close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parishioners at a Roman Catholic church held a
prayer service Sunday, a week after the church was ordered to close,
but an Archdiocese of Detroit spokesman said the action was
understandable.
   About 50 members of Mother of Consolation Church held a 45-minute
prayer service, said Dario Guidarini, president of the parish
council. It was not a formal Mass.
   ``There's no problem with that,'' said archdiocese spokesman Jay
Berman. ``I'm presuming it was something of a spiritual farewell by
the people who participated.''
   Berman said he didn't know whether any other churches already
ordered closed or merged held similar services Sunday. Seven of the
30 targeted parishes closed Friday and two more closed Saturday,
raising the number closed or merged to 25, the archdiocese said last
week.
   On Friday, attorneys representing 17 of the 30 churches filed a
motion to block the closings with the Michigan Court of Appeals. The
court said it would consider the motion no earlier than Wednesday.
   Earlier in the week, Wayne County Circuit Judge James Hathaway
denied a request to block some of the closings, saying civil courts
had no jurisdiction over internal church policy.
   Appeals to the Vatican to overrule Cardinal Edmund Szoka, who
ordered the closings and mergers last fall, also have been rejected.
The church cites declining membership, a shortage of priests and the
costs of maintaining the large churches.
   At least one of the churches have already been sold to a
Protestant congregation.
   Guidarini said he believed church members would comply with a
court decision upholding the archdiocese's order.
   ``We'll talk, but if the appeals court rules against the people,
we probably will surrender the key,'' he said.
</TEXT>
