<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-89 1710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DeSotoSword     07-02 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-De Soto Sword,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three `Pot Hunters' Awarded Ownership Of Historic Spanish Sword</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ancient Spanish sword found on a farm in
northwestern Georgia belongs to the three artifact hunters who dug
it up, not the owner of the farm because he waited too long to claim
it, a judge has ruled.
   Floyd County Superior Court Judge Larry Salmon ordered that the
sword be returned to the three men who dug it up on John Dickey's
land on the Coosa River in 1982, without Dickey's knowledge or
permission.
   Studies indicate the sword was taken to a Coosa Indian village at
the site during the Spanish explorations of Hernando de Soto in 1540
or during a later Spanish expedition in 1560. The village was
attacked in the mid-16th century, and many of the people were killed
by metal weapons.
   Research indicates the sword was made in Spain between 1520 and
1540, and it is an important link establishing that Spaniards came
through Floyd County in the 16th century, Dickey said.
   ``It's going to be a shame if goes somewhere else,'' he said.
   According to the court order filed Friday, Dickey waited too long
before claiming the sword, which had been loaned to the state-run
Etowah Mounds Archaeological Museum. He did not claim ownership
until 1987, after a four-year statute of limitations had run out.
   Dickey said Sunday he did not try to get the sword, known as ``De
Soto's sword,'' back sooner because University of Georgia
archaeologists assured him they were pursuing ownership for the
state.
   Dickey said he first learned of its existence in 1983, when
university archaeologists called him to say the sword that had been
loaned for five years to the Etowah Mounds museum had come from his
farm.
   He said it was taken without his knowledge by ``pot hunters,''
who often enter the dig site. He eventually learned that he had to
file a claim in order to keep the sword from going to the finders,
but it was too late, he said.
   Dickey said he will appeal, adding, ``they admitted themselves
they took it from my place.''
   One of the finders, Larry Itson of Cave Spring, said he is
pleased with Salmon's decision.
   ``I do feel it belongs to us,'' Itson said. ``It was just a real
lucky find _ we weren't trying to steal it.''
   He said he and the other two are seeking a permanent home for the
sword.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
