<SECOND>AM-Barricaded Nuns,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuns Who Left Monastery Keeping Their Reasons and Location a Secret</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three barricaded nuns who fled their Morris
Township monastery after a nearly nine-month standoff are in hiding,
but will continue their protest against liberalizations of their
order, a relative said Sunday.
   One of the Carmelite nuns remained locked in the monastery's
infirmary on Sunday, refusing to leave.
   ``They're not giving up,'' said Anne Ercolano, mother of Sister
Maria, one of those who abandoned the monastery early Saturday
morning.
   ``They left because they want to protect their vows,'' Ms.
Ercolano said in a telephone interview Sunday from her home in
Castleton, N.Y. ``They plan on keeping their appeal going as long as
it takes to set things straight.''
   The four nuns had been barricaded in the infirmary of the
Monastery of the Most Blessed Mary of Mount Carmel since Oct. 4,
when their protest shattered the calm behind the building's
white-stone walls and drew international attention.
   The Carmelite order teaches solitude and prayer with a strict
adherence to separation from the outside world. The rebel nuns have
said they took refuge in the infirmary because they feared eviction
by their mother superior, Prioress Teresa Hewitt, for speaking out
against liberalizations she introduced such as television and sweets.
   During the first days of the protest, Mother Hewitt held news
conferences from behind iron bars, denouncing the unruly members of
her flock for ``attempted anarchy.'' Repeated calls to her telephone
number Sunday got only a busy signal.
   The separation took its emotional and physical toll on the
protesters, Ms. Ercolano said, and led them to leave the infirmary
for more comfortable surroundings while the fight continues. She
refused to say where her daughter and the other nuns have gone.
   ``They're getting fresh air, and for once, they're getting some
peace and quiet,'' Ms. Ercolano said. ``They don't want to be
bothered. They just want the case to go forward.''
   The nuns have said they have an appeal before the Apostolica
Signatura, the highest court at the Vatican. Lower arms of the
Vatican have twice ordered the nuns to end the protest, but they
refused and promised to continue protesting until hearing from the
Apostolica Signatura.
   Paterson Diocese spokesman Tim Manning said the diocese was to
serve them notice Monday that if they did not leave, proceedings
would begin to remove them from the order.
   ``That needs to be re-evaluated before the diocese decides the
next move,'' Manning said. ``There are regulations within the order
forbidding the nuns to leave the monastery for any reason with very
few exceptions, and those regulations will have to be reviewed too.''
   Betty Sutton, a lay person who has served as a spokeswoman for
the nuns, said she did not know they were leaving or where they are.
   ``I've noticed a change in their attitude in the last month, as
if somebody was in contact with them who they've been listening
to,'' Mrs. Sutton said.
   The nuns had been questioning their own tactics in the past few
weeks, after adamantly believing they were doing the right thing,
Mrs. Sutton said.
   They thought their protest remained valid even when a letter from
the Vatican ordered them out of the infirmary, she said.
   Five nuns began the protest in October: Sisters John of the
Cross, Philomena, Bernadette, Maria and Teresita.
   Sister John, now Nicole Prescott, returned to her Hillside home
in March citing health reasons.
   Sister Teresita remained in the infirmary.
   Ms. Ercolano said Sister Teresita did not think the nuns should
have left because she felt the monastery was their home.
   Manning said he did not know what would happen with Sister
Teresita. That would be part of a review set for Monday, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
