<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-02 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain, High Wind Across Parts Of South, Into Ohio Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms with damaging wind developed Sunday over the
southern Plains, very heavy rain fell along parts of the Gulf of
Mexico coast, and thunderstorms also broke out on the northern
Plains and near the Great Lakes.
   Record high temperatures were recorded in southwestern Texas. By
midafternoon, Midland reached a record 108 degrees and San Angelo
had tied its mark of 105.
   In contrast, clouds kept temperatures in the chilly 50s and 60s
across the Pacific Northwest.
   Thunderstorms produced wind gusts to between 60 and 70 mph at
more than a dozen locations in central Oklahoma during the morning.
Siding was blown off a house at Enid and wind blew down utility
poles in Lindsay, the National Weather Service said. Thunderstorms
also hit Kansas.
   The combination of a low pressure area in the upper atmosphere
and the remnants of Tropical Storm Allison produced a large area of
rain from the central Gulf Coast to the lower Ohio Valley.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 1 p.m. CDT included
2.05 inches at Wichita, Kan., and 1.26 inches at Evansville, Ind.
   Flash flood watches were posted for south-central and
southeastern Kentucky, central and southeastern Tennessee and
northern and western Alabama.
   Thunderstorms produced locally heavy rain across the central Gulf
Coast states.
   Along the Mississippi Gulf Coast, 5.22 inches of rain fell at
Biloxi, and 3.94 inches fell at Gulfport in about three hours during
the morning. Gulfport got 9.19 inches of rain between midnight and 1
p.m. CDT.
   Four inches of rain fell between midnight and noon CDT at
Cordova, Ala.
   A thunderstorm produced a tornado that caused slight damage in
Mobile County, Ala., the weather service said. A tornado also
occurred briefly at Long Beach, Miss., but no damage was reported.
   Louisiana rivers continued to rise in the aftermath of record
rainfall from the remnants of Tropical Storm Allison, with scattered
storms and showers replacing the unremitting rain of the previous
five days. One town got nearly 29 inches of rain in less than a week.
   Intense thunderstorms moved across northeastern North Dakota and
northern Minnesota during the morning. Hail the size of marbles fell
at Cavalier, N.D., and wind gusted to 50 mph near Whitman, N.D.
   Thunderstorms also developed over sections of northern Indiana
and southwestern Lower Michigan, with a wind gust to 58 mph during a
thunderstorm at Muskegon, Mich.
   Elsewhere, thunderstorms were scattered across much of Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 58
degrees at Olympia and Tacoma, Wash., to 108 at Carlsbad, N.M.
Sunday's low in the Lower 48 states was 26 at Truckee, Calif.
   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the central and eastern Gulf Coast to the upper Great Lakes
region, especially over the upper Ohio Valley and southern
Appalachians. A few showers were forecast over the Pacific Northwest.
   Highs only in the 60s and 70s were predicted in the Pacific
Northwest and along most of the California coast; in the 70s over
Maine and in the southern Appalachians; over 100 across parts of
Colorado and Utah; between 100 and 115 from southwestern Texas
across New Mexico to the desert Southwest; and in the 80s and 90s
across most of the rest of the nation.

</TEXT>
