<FIRST>r a AM-SecondAbduction     07-02 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Second Abduction,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Jailed in Death of Second Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother who claimed abductors took her two
baby daughters in nearly identical incidents years apart faces a
court hearing Monday into charges that she concealed the second
infant's death.
   Paula Sims, 29, also faces similar charges in the 1986 death of
her first daughter, although no murder charges in either case have
been filed, authorities said.
   Mrs. Sims, arrested Saturday, was being held in lieu of $250,000
bond in the Madison County Jail, accused of obstruction of justice
and concealing a homicide in the April death of her 6-week-old
daughter, Heather Sims.
   Mrs. Sims and her husband, Robert, reported Heather abducted on
April 29 from their home in this southwestern Illinois city. Her
body was found in a trash can across the Mississippi River in
Missouri several days later.
   In 1986, the couple's firstborn daughter, 13-day-old Loralei, was
reported missing under similar circumstances from their previous
home in Jersey County. Mrs. Sims was charged in May with concealing
a homicide and obstructing justice in that case. She pleaded
innocent, and her trial is set for July 18.
   Mrs. Sims was arrested at her parents' home Saturday evening in
the Heather Sims case, said Madison County Sheriff's Police Sgt. Don
Wein.
   Her attorney, Donald Groshong, could not be reached for comment.
A woman who answered his home phone Sunday said he would not be
available until Wednesday. Mrs. Sims' father also refused to talk
Sunday about the latest charges filed against her.
   ``There won't be any information released on the investigation,''
said Alton police Detective Sgt. Bill Lawrence.
   State's Attorney William Haine has said Madison County police are
moving carefully in their investigation of Heather's death and that
no charges would be brought until police had a strong case.
   Police have said Robert Sims told them he believes his wife may
have killed their daughters accidently. Witnesses have said Mrs.
Sims wanted to give birth to sons, and was unhappy with daughters.
   On June 17, 1986, the Simses told police that a masked gunman
broke into their home in Brighton and abducted Loralei. The
decomposed remains of a baby believed to be Loralei were found
several days later near the couple's home in Brighton, a rural
Jersey County community.
   The Simses refused to answer questions before a grand jury that
considered the case in 1987, citing their Fifth Amendment protection
against self-incrimination. The panel took no action.
   But an investigation into the death of Heather uncovered new
evidence in the first case. A Jersey County grand jury returned an
indictment May 12.
   Police have said previously that Robert Sims is a suspect in both
deaths, but he has not been charged. Attempts to reach Sims for
comment were unsuccessful. Sims' father, Troy, reached by telephone,
said he did not know where his son was.
</TEXT>
