<FIRST>u i AM-VanCliburn     07-02 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Van Cliburn,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Virtuoso's Return to Moscow Triumphant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American pianist Van Cliburn, who warmed the hearts
of Soviet music lovers in the midst of the Cold War, on Sunday
repeated the spectacular performance of the piano concerto that
launched his career 31 years ago.
   With roses from the audience at his feet, Cliburn drew bravos and
even screams Sunday night at Tchaikovsky Hall as he performed
Tchaikovsky's Piano Concerto No. 1.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, joined in the
standing ovation and later expressed their enjoyment privately in a
35-minute meeting backstage with the towering 54-year-old Texan and
his 92-year-old mother.
   ``He played like a god,'' said Dallas Morning News critic John
Ardoin, who flew to Moscow to review the performance. ``I don't see
how anyone under this pressure and much emotion could play like he
did.''
   Before playing, Cliburn told the 1,500 people packed into the
oval hall, ``For 31 years, I have felt like I had two homes. I will
soon be asking permission from your distinguished President
Gorbachev to buy an apartment in Moscow. I will be coming for
much-needed visits for my music, for my soul, to Russia and to
Moscow.''
   Gorbachev and his wife laughed even before the request for an
apartment in housing-short Moscow was translated into Russian. But
Cliburn protested, ``Mr. President, I was serious!''
   Cliburn, who lives in Fort Worth, Texas, said after his meeting
with the Gorbachevs that the Soviet leader told him he would help
arrange the apartment.
   Sunday was Cliburn's third performance in 11 years. He came out
of retirement to play for the Gorbachevs at the White House in 1987.
He will play Monday night at the Tchaikovsky Conservatory, on the
same stage where he triumphed in 1958.
   During applause for the Tchaikovsky concerto, many in the hall
were briefly stunned when a television light next to the Gorbachevs'
box exploded. The Soviet president calmly leaned out, looked at the
smoking light stand and resumed clapping.
   As is typical in the Soviet Union, the concert hall had no air
conditioning and the heat was oppressive. Enthusiastic fans crowded
the aisles while hundreds more waited outside for a glimpse of
Cliburn.
   The pianist, his waves of hair perfectly coifed despite the heat,
also played Liszt's Piano Concerto No. 1 in E-flat Major, a Debussy
prelude and the Schumann-Liszt Widmung.
   One of those in the audience was Nake Flock, who said she heard
Cliburn play in Moscow in 1958, when he won the Tchaikovsky
Competition for young pianists with his performance of the
Tchaikaovsky concerto.
   Ms. Flock said she flew to Moscow from her home in Leipzig, East
Germany, and paid $46.50 for a concert ticket that had a face value
of $3.41.
   ``His technique hasn't changed,'' said Ms. Flock, the mother of a
piano student at the Tchaikovsky Conservatory. ``But he has become
more impulsive, more sentimental.''
   Some 20 players in the Moscow Philharmonic Orchestra backing him
were members of the same ensemble 31 years ago that accompanied him
on the night he won the Tchaikovsky Competition.
   The Gorbachevs toasted Cliburn with tea, apple pie and red wine,
said Susan Tilley, president of the Van Cliburn Foundation in Fort
Worth, Texas, who was one of a handful of people allowed into the
meeting. The foundation sponsors an international piano competition
and concert series.
   ``They said come back any time,'' Cliburn said after the meeting.
</TEXT>
