<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-89 1815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Rushmore-Roosevelt     07-02 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rushmore-Roosevelt,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Mount Rushmore, Lujan Calls For Rebirth of Teddy Roosevelt's Ideals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET BROKAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT RUSHMORE NATIONAL MEMORIAL, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Theodore Roosevelt,
celebrated in stone on Mount Rushmore 50 years ago, should be
celebrated today for his environmental spirit, Interior Secretary
Manuel Lujan Jr. said Sunday.
   ``We're not here just to talk about stewardship of our natural
resources. ... We're here to act,'' Lujan told an estimated 4,000 to
5,000 people who turned out to commemorate the 50th anniversary of
the unveiling of Roosevelt's face on the monument.
   As the audience sang along with a military band that played ``God
Bless America,'' a song introduced at the original dedication of
Roosevelt's chiseled face 50 years ago, a 90-by-45-foot U.S. flag
that had been hung on the mountain was drawn back to reveal the
sculpture once again.
   When sculptor Gutzon Borglum decided Roosevelt's features would
be carved next to the 60-foot-tall faces of George Washington,
Thomas Jefferson and Abraham Lincoln, many people wondered if
Roosevelt really belonged with the other presidents on the granite
mountain.
   But Lujan and other speakers said Roosevelt was a good choice for
the huge sculpture known as the Shrine of Democracy because he was a
president for the common person and a leader in the conservation
movement.
   Lujan said President Bush's administration is dedicated to
protecting the environment by reducing acid rain, reversing damage
to the ozone layer, restoring wetland nesting areas for waterfowl
and protecting endangered species.
   The administration will work to promote the nation's economic
growth, but not at the expense of the environment, said the interior
secretary, who played key roles in environmental legislation during
two decades in Congress.
   ``Make no mistake about it: Our commitment to conserving our
natural resources ... will never be sacrificed to corporate
profit,'' he said.
   The huge red, white and blue flag was not placed in front of the
sculpture as scheduled at dawn because of wind gusting to 35 mph.
   A crew of workers on the mountain raised the 300-pound banner for
the first time at mid-morning, quickly lowering it because the wind
was too strong, threatening their safety and the flag itself.
   The program stayed on schedule as winds dropped and work crews
hoisted the flag into position during the speeches, which were given
in the ampitheater at the base of Mount Rushmore.
   Gov. George Mickelson said it was fitting that Roosevelt was
honored on the mountain because he traveled extensively in the
territory that would become the state of South Dakota several
decades before becoming president in 1901.
   Roosevelt first arrived in the 1880s to hunt and buy ranch land
in the area that later became North Dakota, Mickelson said.
   The governor said Roosevelt's travels in the West led to his
later efforts to conserve the nation's resources and to place more
than 100 million acres of forest land into the public trust.
   ``He knew that somehow, the hills and forests we love so much
must be protected for future generations,'' Mickelson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890702-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-89 1842EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     07-02 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Kills Two at Festival Attended By President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese extremists Sunday stormed a
crowded festival attended by President Ranasinghe Premadasa and key
Cabinet members and set off a bomb that killed at least two people,
police said.
   Premadasa and the Cabinet ministers were in a secret well-guarded
location and were unharmed, authorities said. Thirty people were
injured, many critically.
   No one claimed responsibility for the blast, which occurred
shortly after midnight Saturday near Mahiyangana, about 70 miles
northeast of Colombo. Police blamed the left-wing People's
Liberation Front, which opposes tactics used by the government to
end the insurgency by Tamil rebels.
   Police would not say if the attack was aimed at anyone in
particular.
   ``It could have been at anybody. We don't know,'' said one police
officer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Elsewhere, authorities said security forces arrested 3,237 youths
suspected of belonging to the People's Liberation Front. It was the
single largest crackdown against the group in nearly two years.
   Also Sunday, 18 people were reported killed by Sinhalese hit
squads in central and northern Sri Lanka.
   Tamils, who comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
contend they are discriminated against in jobs and education.
Sinhalese make up 75 percent of the population and control the
government and military.
   According to police in Mahiyangana, several armed youths entered
the grounds where 200,000 to 300,000 people gathered for the 11th
Annual Village Reawakening Festival, and they exploded a bomb near
the main stage.
   The 10-day festival is aimed at encouraging people to build
better houses for themselves and to repair their rundown villages.
   The attack, the first on such a festival, came despite increased
security, including the posting of a large number of military
commands around the grounds.
   The People's Liberation Front has been blamed for more than 3,500
killings since July 1987, when Indian peacekeeping forces arrived on
this troubled island to enforce a peace accord between the
Sinhalese-dominated government and militant Tamils, who have been
fighting for a separate homeland since 1983.
   The front contends the accord grants too many concessions to the
minority Tamils, and it says the presence of Indian soldiers
threatens Sri Lanka's sovereignty. Front members have vowed to kill
anyone who supports the pact.
   India became involved in the ethnic problems of the nation
because its own 60 million Tamils are sympathetic to the rebel cause.
   In addition to the bombing, police blamed Sinhalese extremists
for the deaths of seven moderate Sinhalese in Kurunegala, about 65
miles northeast of Colombo, and for seven other deaths in Colombo.
   Officers also said they found four Sinhalese youths shot to death
in the town of Kegalle, 50 miles northeast of Colombo.
   Armed with automatic weapons and empowered by tough emergency
laws, soldiers and police raided homes and arrested 3,200 suspected
radicals in the Sinhalese-dominated south, officials said.
   Armed troops also forced open a hostel in Colombo and arrested 37
medical interns who allegedly belong to the front. The weekend
newspaper Sun claimed the medical facullty of Colombo University has
