<FIRST>r a AM-CivilRights-King     07-02 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Civil Rights-King,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>SCLC Commemorates Civil Rights Bill With Challenge To Bush, Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights leaders commemorated the day their
movement became law Sunday by praying at the crypt of Martin Luther
King Jr. and challenging President Bush to live up to his stated
commitment to their cause.
   ``Mr. Bush has got to get up and make the White House the right
house,'' said the Rev. Joseph Lowery, president of the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference. ``It's not enough to talk that
talk. We need him to walk that walk.''
   The SCLC was marking the 25th anniversary of the passage of the
Civil Rights Act of 1964, which banned segregation in public
facilities and has been used in court actions against discrimination
in the workplace.
   Lowery, one of several civil rights leaders who met with Bush
Friday, said recent Supreme Court decisions against affirmative
action programs have left black leaders doubting that the president
would work to protect progress made under the law.
   ``I'm going to remain hopeful for the time being,'' Lowery said.
``Mr. Bush has good instincts. He wants to do what's right in this
regard.''
   On Friday, Bush called on Congress to reauthorize the Civil
Rights Commission, which is set to expire Nov. 30. But earlier last
week, Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said the Bush administration
would not push Congress to overturn the Supreme Court decisions.
   Lowery said civil rights leaders are concerned that Bush's latest
statements might be just rhetoric, and added that Bush is ``gonna
have to make up his mind'' on either bolstering black membership in
the GOP or pleasing ultra-conservatives.
   Lowery was joined at King's gravesite by Rosa Parks, whose
refusal to sit in a segregated section of a Montgomery, Ala., bus in
1955 sparked the civil rights movement.
   Mrs. Parks said Bush's statements ``sounded good, but we are
waiting for real, real action.''
   ``We cannot lull ourselves to sleep with words,'' she said.
   About 200 people gathered for the prayer service, during which
Lowery blasted Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor for her
position against affirmative action.
   ``Glory be to God, if it weren't for affirmative action she'd
still be in Arizona presiding over a microwave,'' Lowery said,
adding that the American public should ``remind Sandra who she is.''
   ``We bled too profusely and died too young to let any Supreme
Court turn us around,'' Lowery said.
</TEXT>
