<SECOND>AM-Marcos, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0760,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Imelda Marcos: Ferdinand's Life Is Best Birthday Present</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `After the...,' to CORRECT that book was given
shortly before indictment, sted after.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
clung to life in a Honolulu hospital Sunday, and his wife Imelda
said that made her 60th birthday happy.
   ``I would like to thank Ferdinand for the best birthday present
he has ever given me _ his life,'' the former Philippine First Lady
said after a Roman Catholic Mass at the couple's home-in-exile here.
   Marcos, who was president of the Philippines for 20 years before
being ousted in February 1986, remained in critical condition Sunday
at St. Francis Medical Center, where he has been hospitalized since
January.
   The exiled ruler has suffered massive organ failure, is battling
a widespread infection and is being kept alive by machines.
   ``I know he survived all of this because God has blessed us with
a miracle,'' Mrs. Marcos said.
   After the Mass, Mrs. Marcos read the inscription in a book her
husband of 35 years gave her last October, shortly before the couple
was indicted in the United States for allegedly stealing more than
$100 million from the Philippine treasury and stashing it in the
United States.
   Marcos wrote the book to chronicle his version of the events that
led to his downfall.
   In the inscription, Marcos promised not to try to regain power if
allowed home.
   Asked later whether Mrs. Marcos read the inscription as a message
to Philippine President Corazon Aquino, who has steadfastly refused
to let the Marcoses come home, she replied, ``It's a message to all
of humanity ... of everyone's right to freedom.''
   But she admitted she was not optimistic that Mrs. Aquino, who
claims Marcos stole billions of dollars during his rule, would
relent.
</TEXT>
