<FIRST>r e BC-JazzFestival     07-02 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Jazz Festival,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>JVC Jazz Festival Ends with Clark Terry and Friends</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's JVC Jazz Festival ended with a
tribute to trumpeter Clark Terry that was a neatly planned,
well-played concert which built to an exciting set with master
musicians Oscar Peterson and Louis Bellson.
   Terry invited the musicians and was the featured performer on
``Clark Terry and Friends'' at Town Hall on Saturday night.
   The final set had Peterson on piano, Bellson on drums, Kenny
Burrell on electric guitar and bassist Victor Gasklin. Terry joined
them on their fourth number, to play a warm solo on ``My Romance.''
   The evening began with a group representing the Big B-A-D Band
that Terry formed in 1970. The trombone section was featured on
``Blues in My Shoes.'' Terry sang ``I Want a Little Girl,'' backed
by saxophonist Lew Tabackin, a charming interlude.
   Irene Reid sang, accompanied by pianist Don Friedman, drummer
Butch Ballard, who once played with Elmer Snowden, and bassist
Marcus McLaurine. She was effective with a song without rhymes or
repeated musical phrases, with a lush Duke Ellington tune and a
string of Count Basie blues songs.
   ``Trumpets No End,'' the arrangement of ``Blue Skies'' that Mary
Lou Williams did featuring six trumpets in the Ellington Band, gave
its name to a segment by seven trumpet players. After Jimmy Owens,
Bob Montgomery, Rod McGahie, Joe Newman, Johnny Helms and Terry
played solos, Jon Faddis pretty much wiped them up with high notes,
speed and clear, long-held notes.
   Terry played in the bands of Lionel Hampton, Charlie Barnet,
Count Basie and, from 1951 to '59, Duke Ellington. After that he was
regularly on the Tonight Show, then played with Peterson. He led a
group with Bob Brookmeyer in the 1970s. At Town Hall Terry's sense
of humor surfaced when he recited, with feeling and emphatic
gestures, a poem in nonsense syllables.
   The next to last set was called Clark Terry and the Spacemen,
because Ellington, inspired by Sputnik, called small groups from his
band the Spacemen. Saturday night's included Aaron Bell, who played
bass for Ellington, on piano, other Ellington alumni, Jimmy
Hamilton, Britt Woodman and Norris Turney, plus Haywood Henry,
Virgil Jones, Ballard and bassist Victor Gaskin.
   They played an Ellington set, ``Jones,'' ``Primpin' for the
Prom,'' a smoothly mellow ``Mood Indigo'' and a rousing ``In a
Mellowtone.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
