<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0691 07-02 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0691,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ten Killed in Syrian Shelling and Inter-Shiite Gun Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs at bottom to UPDATE with two Israeli-allied militiamen
wounded in south. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners blasted the Christian
sector of the Lebanese capital with shellfire Sunday, and rival
militias backed by Syria and Iran clashed in street battles in
Moslem west Beirut, police said.
   Ten people were killed and 29 wounded, they said.
   A Soviet envoy and the foreign ministers of three Arab countries
working for a settlement of Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war arrived
in Syria.
   Since the latest round of fighting began in March, 396 people
have been killed and 1,532 wounded.
   Police said eight people were killed Sunday and 20 wounded in the
Syrian bombardment of Christian east Beirut's sprawling residential
districts of Ashrafiyeh and Furn el-Shubbak.
   One shell crashed into the bedroom of Antoine Abi-Aad, 31, a
Maronite Catholic priest, and his wife Renee, 24, in Ashrafiyeh.
They were killed as they slept, said a police spokesman, who cannot
be named under standing rules.
   The Syrians also pounded a 25-mile coastal stretch to prevent
food, fuel and arms supplies from reaching the Christian enclave
north of Beirut, police said. Christian militia gunners responded
with intermittent barrages of 155mm shellfire.
   The police spokesman said two people were killed and nine wounded
in the fighting between the Moslem militias. The gun battles raged
all night and through Sunday morning between the Syrian-backed
Shiite Moslem Amal militia and the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or party
of God.
   It was the first major clash between the factions since the death
of Iran's revolutionary patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini on
June 3.
   The fundamentalist Hezbollah and the more secular Amal have been
fighting for control of the million-strong Shiite community, the
largest single sect in Lebanon.
   The latest round of fighting in Lebanon's civil war broke out on
March 8 between army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's 20,000 troops,
most of them Christians, and an alliance of Syria's 40,000 troops
and Druse forces. Hezbollah and Amal had stayed out of that
confrontation.
   Soviet envoy Alexander Bessmertnykh flew to Damascus after
winning a pledge from Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's government,
Syria's main Arab foe, to halt arms shipments to the Lebanese
Christians if the Syrians stopped their daily bombardment of the
Christian enclave.
   Syria's government newspaper Al-Thawra said the Iraqi pledge was
``a maneuver ... to mislead the Arab League committee.''
   Bessmertnykh carried a message from Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev to Syrian President Hafez Assad, said a Soviet source who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Syria and Iraq have close ties with Moscow. The Soviets were
Iraq's main arms suppliers during the eight-year Iran-Iraq war, and
Syria is Moscow's leading Arab ally.
   The Arab League committee includes King Hassan II of Morocco,
King Fahd of Saudi Arabia and President Chadli Bendjedid of Algeria.
The 22-nation Arab League has asked the committee to find a
settlement to Lebanon's war by November.
   But so far it has been unable to enforce even a cease-fire called
in May.
   The foreign ministers of the three countries were in Damascus to
discuss the truce violations.
   Aoun lashed out at the Arab committee for keeping silent on
Syrian violations of the cease-fire.
   ``The Arab committee is becoming a helpless spectator while the
Syrians persist in their daily defiance of the Arab League
cease-fire calls. This is pushing the Lebanese to despair,'' he said
in a statement broadcast by Christian radio stations.
   ``If the Arab League, which is supported by the United Nations,
is incapable of making the Syrians respect its resolutions, then it
must declare the Syrians as the defiers,'' Aoun said.
   Syria entered Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League mandate to halt
the civil war. Christians say the Syrians lost their role as neutral
peacekeepers because they have sided with Moslems in the civil war.
   Meanwhile, in southern Lebanon, two militiamen of the
Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army were wounded Sunday when their
armored personnel carrier hit a mine, police reported.
   A police spokesman said the explosion occurred in Kfar Falous in
Israel's self-declared ``security zone,'' a strip of Lebanese border
territory the Israelis have occupied since 1985.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named under standing regulations,
said the Lebanese militia retaliated by shelling the villages of
Ka'kaiyat il-Jisr and Zoutar Sharqiyyeh. No casualties were reported.
</TEXT>
