<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Election 1stLd-Writethru   07-02 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0774,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Pulls Ahead in Tokyo Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with early results. CORRECTS to
Tokyo Metropolitan Assembly, sted Municipal; Picks up 8th pvs, `The Kyodo...';
SUBS final graf `The poll...' to fix typo. CHANGES byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition socialists pulled ahead of the
governing Liberal Democratic Party on Monday in municipal elections
viewed as a gauge of how well the scandal-ridden Liberal Democrats
will fare in national elections.
   Women were expected to tilt the vote in favor of the opposition
following a campaign that focused on a sex scandal in the governing
party.
   With 47 of the 128 seats in the Tokyo Metropolitan Assembly
decided, the Japan Socialist Party had won 22, nine more than the
Liberal Democrats, according to the Japan Broadcasting Corp.
   The early results were considered significant since the
Socialists held only 11 assembly seats coming into Sunday's
election. The Liberal Democrats had 63.
   The Clean Government Party had five seats, the Communist Party
three, and independent candidates had won four, the television
network said.
   About 5.18 million people, or 58.7 percent of the eligible
voters, cast ballots Sunday. That was up from 53.5 percent in the
last election in 1985, the Tokyo Board of Elections said.
   The election was being closely watched as a sign of how the
Liberal Democrats, who have ruled Japan since 1954, will do in a
national election July 23 for half the seats in the upper house of
the parliament, or Diet.
   More than 61 percent of registered women voted, compared to 56.16
percent of men, the board said.
   The high turnout, especially among women, was expected to favor
the opposition. The opposition campaign focused on national issues,
including an unpopular 3 percent consumption tax passed by the
Liberal Democratic Party; an influence-peddling scandal that forced
the resignation of Prime Minster Noboru Takeshita; and a sex scandal
centering on reports the new prime minister, Sousuke Uno, has kept
paid mistresses.
   The Kyodo News Service reported a women's group in Miyazaki,
western Japan, gathered signatures from more than 1,000 women on a
petition for the prime minister saying, ``It is an embarrassment for
Japan to be represented at the summit by a person who tramples over
women.''
   Uno took office last month, and soon afterward, Japanese media
published an interview with a former geisha who said Uno paid her
for sex. The woman later appeared in a television interview, and
reports that Uno kept other mistresses filled the press last week.
   The scandal has further tainted the Liberal Democratic Party,
which was badly shaken by the so-called Recruit scandal, which
forced the resignation of Takeshita on June 2.
   The scandal involved the Recruit Co., a publishing conglomerate
accused of handing out millions of dollars in political
contributions and bargain-priced stock in exchange for political
favors.
   Only 25 percent of Tokyo voters polled recently by the Asahi
Shimbun newspaper said they planned to support Liberal Democrat
candidates, down from 34 percent who expressed support in 1985.
   A Kyodo News Service poll released Thursday showed 16 percent
supporting the Japan Socialist Party, the main opposition party,
while support for the Liberal Democrats had fallen from 42.4 to only
13.2 percent.
   A poll published in the Mainichi Shimbun, a national daily, said
the ruling party was likely to lose heavily.
   The poll showed women were breaking away from the Liberal
Democratic Party. Women who said they would shift from the governing
party to the socialists jumped from 8 percent to 18 percent, while
those who said they would vote for the Liberal Democrats shrank from
33 to 18 percent.
</TEXT>
