<FIRST>u i AM-Cuba-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru   07-02 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0664,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former General Says He Dealt in Drugs to Invest in Tourism</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS 4 grafs at end to add Reuters correspondent expelled.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former major general in the Cuban military
testified at his court-martial that he trafficked drugs because he
wanted to invest in tourism projects like hotels, the Cuban news
agency said Sunday.
   Arnaldo Ochoa Sanchez, who received medals for his wartime deeds,
is one of 15 high-ranking military officers charged with high
treason and trafficking in cocaine, diamonds and ivory.
   They were stripped of their rank and expelled from the Communist
Party last week. Three major generals began hearing the case Friday.
The 15 could face the firing squad if convicted.
   The Cuban government news agency Prensa Latina said Sunday that
Ochoa and two aides, Jorge Martinez and Antonio Rodriguez, admitted
their actions ``seriously endangered the prestige, morality and
dignity of Cuba, its armed forces, people and government.''
   The agency said they ``showed themselves on Cuban TV to be
convinced that their guilt of narcotics trafficking and other crimes
requires the most severe sanction.''
   Earlier dispatches from Havana said the defendants belonged to a
secret division of the Interior Ministry that smuggled medicine,
hospital supplies and computers to circumvent a U.S. trade embargo.
One of the defendants is former Interior Minister Jose Abrantes.
   Ochoa said on Sunday that he was ``thinking big'' when he decided
to become involved in international drug trafficking in 1987, Prensa
Latina said.
   He said he planned to invest large amounts of money in hotel
construction but did not intend to turn the island into a drug
trafficking center.
   Ochoa said he had opened an account at the Banco Viscaya in
Panama in 1985. He did not give the purpose of the account, but said
it was unrelated to drug trafficking.
   The defendants are accused of helping Colombia's Medellin drug
cartel smuggle cocaine into the United States. Ochoa and some of the
others have said they dealt in cocaine to earn dollars to help
Cuba's faltering economy.
   As a major general, Ochoa took part in or directed fighting in
Angola and Ethiopia, and served on missions in Venezuela and to help
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista regime.
   Also Sunday, Cuba expelled a correspondent for the Reuters news
service, Gilles Trequesser, for ``falsely and maliciously''
reporting that two Communist Party officials wanted asylum in a
foreign embassy.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Hector Argiles said Trequesser
``falsely and maliciously'' linked ``the alleged search for asylum''
with the drug case.
   Prensa Latina said Trequesser reported that Osmani Cienfuegos, a
member of the Council of State and of the ruling Communist Party's
Political Bureau, and Abraham Maciques, president of the state
trading Corporacion Cubanacan, had asked for asylum at an unnamed
foreign embassy.
   The London-based news agency confirmed the expulsion. It said
Trequesser had been in Cuba for two years.
</TEXT>
