<FIRST>r f AM-SECMove     07-02 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC Move ,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC's NY Regional Office is Moving July 21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The people who helped bring down Ivan F. Boesky
are moving up _ two floors _ and over about seven blocks.
   The New York regional office of the Securities and Exchange
Commission will be trading its longtime base at 26 Federal Plaza in
lower Manhattan for new quarters near the World Trade Center later
this month.
   After more than 20 years at the aging, 42-story government office
building that also houses the FBI, Immigration and Naturalization
Service and some 80 other federal agencies near the city's courts
and municipal buildings, the SEC local staff is moving into private
office space closer to the financial district it regulates.
   The agency will exchange the slighty shabby federal building with
its beige walls and balky elevators for two entire floors atop 75
Park Place, a sleek, glass and metal, 13-story office building that
opened less than two years ago.
   The New York office, biggest of the SEC's nine regional offices,
will be expanding its office space from 34,000 square feet to 40,000
square feet, according to Renee Miscione, a spokeswoman for the
General Services Administration, which administers federal office
buildings.
   Other tenants in the new location include the publisher R.R.
Donnelly &amp; Sons and the legal department of the city's housing
authority.
   While SEC Regional Administrator Lawrence Iason and his staff of
about 200 are happy about the move, they also don't have much choice.
   The 850 staffers of the federal Environmental Protection Agency,
who already occupy parts of 12 floors at 26 Federal Plaza, need more
space and the SEC's offices fit the bill.
   ``But it's not like (the move) isn't beneficial,'' Dorothy Heyl,
regional counsel for the SEC in New York, said during a recent
interview as she tried to find room for storing 100 office chairs
that arrived three weeks early.
   The public reference room, where company filings and other SEC
documents are made available, will be expanded slightly, said Iason.
</TEXT>
